<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06198082 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06198082 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  GOVERNMENT; SUPPORT; LEADER; INDIA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  New Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao won a vote of confidence Monday andpromised to seek consensus as he administers his unstable minoritygovernment.;    Rao appeared to be trying to appease the divided opposition,which can topple the government at any time by uniting. Rao's Congress Partyis nine seats short of a majority in Parliament.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NEW INDIAN LEADER WINS VOTE OF CONFIDENCE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;The consensus we need might elude us sometimes, but that is the only wayof running the government successfully hereafter,&quot; Rao said before the vote inParliament's lower house, the Lok Sabha.;    The Congress Party won the vote241-111. The largest opposition party, the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party,voted against the one-line motion, and the Left Front and centrist NationalFront of former Prime Minister V.P. Singh abstained. As a coalition, the Leftand National fronts control 126 seats.;    Rao's 3-week-old government willneed the cooperation of the fronts to push legislation through thepolicy-making house of Parliament, which has 507 seats.;    Rao became leaderof the centrist Congress Party after the May 21 assassination of former PrimeMinister Rajiv Gandhi.;    His most pressing problems are a financial crisisand separatist insurgencies by Sikhs in Punjab, Muslims in Kashmir andAssamese in the remote northeastern state of Assam.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New Delhi, India  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910716  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  26C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  210  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday July 16, 199100198082,SJ1 